c

	quXaAEirN Rough to the touch; 
	xaXinu AlmasRi: (K, accord. to the TA:) or rough, and advanced in years; 
	xaXinN musinRN, with the art. AlxaXinu AlmusinRu. (CK, and a MS. copy of the K.)

7 AnqDR c
7. AnqDR It (a thing) broke, or became broken. (Msb.) Said of a wall, it signifies the same: (T, Msb, TA:) or it became thrown down, pulled down, pulled to pieces, demolished, or destroyed, with violence: (A:) or it fell down: (S:) or it cracked, without falling down; (M, K;) as also AinoqaADRa [from naqaDa]; inf. n. [of the former] AinoqiDaADN; (K;) [and AinoqaADa, inf. n. AinoqiyaADN;] but if it fall, you say, taqayRaDa, inf. n. taqayRuDN: so says AZ: (TA:) A 'Obeyd and others reckon it a biliteral-radical word, belonging to this art.; (M;) or AZ reckons it as such; (TA;) but Aboo- 'Alee makes it a triliteral-radical, [like its syn. AinoqaADRa,] from naqaDa, holding its measure to be AifoEalRa. (M, TA.) ― -b2- It became cut in pieces. (TA.) ― -b3- [And hence,] AnqDRt OawoSaAluhu (assumed tropical:) His connections became sundered, or separated. (TA.) [See also AnfDR.] ― -b4- [And from AnqDR as explained above on the authority of the S, or of the A, is derived the phrase] AnqDR AlTRaAYiru (S, M, A, &c.) (tropical:) The bird dropped down (S, M, Mgh, Msb, K) swiftly from the air, (Mgh,) in its flight, (S, Msb,) to alight (M, K, TA) upon a thing; (TA;) [i. e. pounced down, darted down, or made a stoop;] as also taqaDRaDa↓ and taqaDRaI↓, (M, K,) the latter of which is formed by permutation; (M;) or only the latter of these two is used; (S;) or the latter of them is the more chaste;
(TA;) for the three dáds are found difficult of pronunciation, and therefore one of them is changed into yé, like as is the case in taZanRaI [for taZanRana], from AlZRanRN, (S, TA,) and tamaTRaI for tamaTRaTa. (TA.) You say, AnqDR AlbaAziI EalaI AlSRayodi The hawk [made a stoop, or] flew down swiftly upon the prey, or quarry. (TA.) ― -b5- Hence, (S,) AnqDR said of a star, or an asterism, (S, A,) (tropical:) [It darted down: or] it dropped down. (TA.) ― -b6- Hence also, (TA,) AnqDRt Ealayohimo Alxayolu (tropical:) The horses, or horsemen, rushed, or went swiftly, upon them, or against them: (S, * TA:) or dispersed themselves, or became dispersed, against them, or upon them. (M, K.)
